    text: `You are designing the character customisation screen for a F2P hero shooter on PS5, Xbox, PC, and Switch. 16 heroes, 8 equipment slots, 40-80 cosmetic items per slot, stat-modifying gear with comparison tooltips, 3D character preview at 30fps on Switch handheld. Controller navigation is primary on console. Target: browse 600+ items, compare stats, preview combinations, and confirm loadout in under 90 seconds between matches. You prototype and find: browsing 600+ items in a flat grid takes 45 seconds to scroll to the bottom on controller. Three navigation approaches: (A) categorised tabs (by rarity, by type, by recent) that reduce any single list to 30-50 items -- fast but requires the player to know which category their desired item is in; (B) a search/filter system with text input -- powerful but on-screen keyboard on console adds 10 seconds per search; (C) a "favourites" system where players pre-select up to 20 items per slot, reducing the between-match browse to a curated shortlist -- fast for returning players but useless for first-time browsing. Choose one as the primary and one as a supplement. Rule out one entirely and state why it fails the 90-second target on controller. For the 3D preview on Switch, state whether you: render at 720p with LOD2 character models, render at 540p upscaled, or replace the 3D preview with a 2D card illustration. State the specific framerate threshold below which you disable the 3D preview entirely.`
